#rstats shiny tip of the day: Need to generate *several* UI elements inside a renderUI()? Use tagList() to group multiple UI elements together. Example: output$x <- renderUI({ tagList( textInput(...), numericInput(...) ) }) Voila! Useful in other situations too.

#rstats tip of the day: Need to fit multiple expressions on one single line? Separate expressions with a semicolon. Useful when need to be very concise. For example: `x <- 5; print(x)` Not recommended in your scripts for long term (style reasons), but can be handy to know.

#rstats beginner tip of the day: When trying to see if a number or text is equal to some *single* value, use `==`. To check it against *multiple* values, use `%in%`. I often see code such as `if(num == c(5, 6))`, which may *seem* to work sometimes, but need to use %in% instead.

#rstats tip of the day: `{}` is a way to have multiple expressions in a place that expects one expression. Example: system.time({ n<-100 rnorm(n) }) wouldn't work without {} because it expects 1 expression This is why in shiny you always see `reactive({})` and `observe({})`

Highly useful alert! If you work with counts #rstats , may I recommend a zero-inflated negative binomial model? https:// stats.idre.ucla.edu/r/dae/zinb/

When in doubt, fit a zero-inflated negative binomial rather than a poisson regression or otherwise. Why? Poisson is nested in the negbin distribution https:// stats.stackexchange.com/a/128640/11509 #rstats The fitdistrplus library is great for this. Another resource https:// stats.idre.ucla.edu/r/dae/zinb/
